`docs/` collects the human-facing reference material for a stenography dictionary compiler and its firmware target — read here before touching the parse/expand/render pipeline, the vendored Pico firmware integration, or before triaging task priority.

`steno-format.md` is the normative grammar for `.steno` source files (entries, directives, template operators) but is explicitly subordinate to `crates/steno/src/parse/` and `dict.steno` — if the two disagree, the code wins and this doc is stale. `pipeline.md` picks up where the format leaves off: it's the architecture map from parsed AST through Pass A/B expansion to the four JSON render targets and the separate infinite-dictionary C++ path, and it documents cross-module invariants (acyclic module deps, typed errors per stage, the Pass B ↔ C++ walker agreement enforced by differential test) that any pipeline change must preserve. `firmware-build.md` is downstream of both — it consumes the *generated* dictionary header as an opaque artifact and documents the separate, non-Rust build (CMake/ARM toolchain/vendored `javelin-steno-pico`) that wires it into a flashable image via tracked patches; it shares no data format with the other two docs beyond "a header file exists." `STATUS.md` is the task tracker; several of its high-impact items (Array<> typing standardization, %T/C++ dict integration) directly reference decisions that `pipeline.md` and `firmware-build.md` describe as already-settled invariants, so a status-item resolution should update the relevant doc, not just close the task.

The shared coupling to watch: `steno-format.md`'s template-operator grammar (`%d`, `%t`, `%(EXPR)`) is exactly the surface `pipeline.md` says Pass A/B must interpret consistently, so a grammar change forces a pipeline.md update and vice versa. Nothing here documents crate-internal APIs — that detail lives in the `.ctx` files under `crates/`.

No intent.md is present, so no divergence check is possible.
